{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/hyponatraemia/background-information/risk-factors/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"f9af97ee-3a11-59b0-9533-e9a4ed3f8900","slug":"risk-factors","fullItemName":"Risk factors","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 3dfd347b-95cd-449b-bc55-a76900ad4b90 --><h2>What are the risk factors?</h2><!-- end field 3dfd347b-95cd-449b-bc55-a76900ad4b90 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item d1d510d6-14b0-4444-a8ef-a76900ad4a13 --><!-- begin field 2245cb65-f6b0-472a-b16f-a76900ad4b90 --><ul><li><strong>The most significant risk factor for hyponatraemia is increasing age <strong>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hyponatraemia/references/\">Chan, 1997</a>]</strong> <strong>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hyponatraemia/references/\">Miller, 1998</a>]</strong> <strong>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hyponatraemia/references/\">BMJ, 2019</a>]</strong>.</strong> <ul><li>Hyponatraemia is common among the elderly and may be caused by disease processes, drugs, and/or physiological changes, including [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hyponatraemia/references/\">GAIN, 2010</a>]:<ul><li>A reduced renal diluting capacity.</li><li>An increased release of <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hyponatraemia/background-information/pathophysiology/\">antidiuretic hormone</a> (ADH) at baseline.</li><li>An increased circulating level of atrial natriuretic peptide.</li></ul></li><li>About half of elderly people with hyponatraemia have features typical of the <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hyponatraemia/background-information/causes/#additional-information-on-causes\">syndrome of inappropriate antidiuresis</a>.</li><li>Medications, thiazide diuretics in particular, are more likely to cause hyponatraemia in elderly people with a low body mass index [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hyponatraemia/references/\">Chow, 2003</a>].</li></ul></li><li><strong>Other risk factors include [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hyponatraemia/references/\">GAIN, 2010</a>]:</strong><ul><li>Hospitalization — hyponatraemia can be present on admission to hospital, or it can develop (or worsen) during the hospital stay, as a result of factors such as organ failure, medications, or the post-operative state.</li><li><a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hyponatraemia/background-information/causes/#additional-information-on-causes\">Medications</a>, such as thiazide diuretics.</li><li><a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hyponatraemia/background-information/causes/#additional-information-on-causes\">Underlying medical conditions</a>, such as congestive heart failure.</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 2245cb65-f6b0-472a-b16f-a76900ad4b90 --><!-- end item d1d510d6-14b0-4444-a8ef-a76900ad4a13 -->","topic":{"id":"0a0a0516-fca2-530d-88cd-096861572e3a","topicId":"560440de-b2ae-4ea7-9fb2-a701015e193f","topicName":"Hyponatraemia","slug":"hyponatraemia","lastRevised":"Last revised in November 2020","chapters":[{"id":"2d0342b8-1d8f-5b76-af1d-5c62137a465c","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"94ef9729-defa-5118-80c3-603843005f8a","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"0e655e55-4b6c-5ca3-9d0a-bcf5afa498d8","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"262d0445-6fa5-53ed-8b8c-037da1983e4f","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"f79882a4-6b50-5264-a45b-2d43249a3418","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"8705184f-c02d-5cb2-9294-d85860c5d56e","fullItemName":"Goals and outco